      "cardText": "TRAUMA RESPONSE PROFILE: Partner travels\n\n1) WHAT SET IT OFF\nEnvironment: Couple\nTrigger: Partner travels\nOld trauma story: Distance means disconnection\nShame sentence: Closeness will expose the parts of me that are unlovable.\n\n2) WHAT YOUR SYSTEM MAY DO\nDominant response: Fawn\nSecondary responses: Fix/Reassurance (4/5)\nBody signal: anxiety\nArousal state: window of tolerance narrowing\nRisk level: 🟠 Moderate\n\n3) WHY THIS RESPONSE MAKES SENSE\nTries to stay connected and prevent punishment by pleasing, apologising, agreeing, or becoming smaller.\n\n4) WHAT IT COSTS\nCan hide true needs, create resentment, and teach others that your limits do not matter.\n\n5) WHAT TO DO FIRST\nPlan check-in rhythm\n\n6) SAFER RESPONSE PLAN\nPause before saying yes, ask 'what do I actually need?', and practise one honest preference. First grounding: Plan check-in rhythm.\n\n7) WORDS YOU CAN USE\nI notice I am agreeing automatically. Please give me time to check what I actually want.\n\n8) SUPPORTER RESPONSE\nDo not reward self-erasure. Gently ask for their real preference and give time to answer.\n\n9) PAKISTAN / CULTURAL NOTE\nModerate cultural relevance; check whether family, class, gender, religion, or workplace hierarchy changes how this trigger is experienced.\n\nRecommended module: Relationship Trigger Map",
