      "cardText": "TRAUMA RESPONSE PROFILE: Silence at night\n\n1) WHAT SET IT OFF\nEnvironment: Bedroom\nTrigger: Silence at night\nOld trauma story: Threat is hidden\nShame sentence: I am unsafe because I failed to see the danger early enough.\n\n2) WHAT YOUR SYSTEM MAY DO\nDominant response: Fight\nSecondary responses: Fold/Collapse (4/5); Fix/Reassurance (4/5); Flight/Avoidance (3/5)\nBody signal: scanning\nArousal state: hyperarousal\nRisk level: 🔴 High\n\n3) WHY THIS RESPONSE MAKES SENSE\nTries to restore control quickly by pushing back, questioning, or defending before the shame can deepen.\n\n4) WHAT IT COSTS\nCan create conflict, guilt, or distance even when the real need is safety and respect.\n\n5) WHAT TO DO FIRST\nAdd neutral sound\n\n6) SAFER RESPONSE PLAN\nPause the next sentence, unclench the jaw, name the boundary without attacking, and return to the facts. First grounding: Add neutral sound. Because this is high risk, involve a safe person or professional support if there is danger, self-harm risk, severe dissociation, or inability to return.\n\n7) WORDS YOU CAN USE\nI am activated and may sound sharper than I mean. I need a pause, a lower voice, and a chance to come back calmly.\n\n8) SUPPORTER RESPONSE\nPrioritise safety, stay present if safe to do so, and involve professional/emergency support when risk is active.\n\n9) PAKISTAN / CULTURAL NOTE\nModerate cultural relevance; check whether family, class, gender, religion, or workplace hierarchy changes how this trigger is experienced.\n\nRecommended module: Night Survival Plan",
