      "cardText": "TRAUMA RESPONSE PROFILE: Saying no\n\n1) WHAT SET IT OFF\nEnvironment: Relationship\nTrigger: Saying no\nOld trauma story: They will be angry or leave\nShame sentence: Closeness will expose the parts of me that are unlovable.\n\n2) WHAT YOUR SYSTEM MAY DO\nDominant response: Fawn\nSecondary responses: Flight/Avoidance (4/5); Fix/Reassurance (4/5)\nBody signal: fawn\nArousal state: mixed\nRisk level: 🔴 High\n\n3) WHY THIS RESPONSE MAKES SENSE\nTries to stay connected and prevent punishment by pleasing, apologising, agreeing, or becoming smaller.\n\n4) WHAT IT COSTS\nCan hide true needs, create resentment, and teach others that your limits do not matter.\n\n5) WHAT TO DO FIRST\nNo is a complete sentence\n\n6) SAFER RESPONSE PLAN\nPause before saying yes, ask 'what do I actually need?', and practise one honest preference. First grounding: No is a complete sentence. Because this is high risk, involve a safe person or professional support if there is danger, self-harm risk, severe dissociation, or inability to return.\n\n7) WORDS YOU CAN USE\nI notice I am agreeing automatically. Please give me time to check what I actually want.\n\n8) SUPPORTER RESPONSE\nPrioritise safety, stay present if safe to do so, and involve professional/emergency support when risk is active.\n\n9) PAKISTAN / CULTURAL NOTE\nModerate cultural relevance; check whether family, class, gender, religion, or workplace hierarchy changes how this trigger is experienced.\n\nRecommended module: Safe Intimacy & Touch",
